<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Types of Class Action Cases</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>Consumer fraud and deceptive practices</h2>
  <p>False advertising, deceptive pricing, hidden fees, and misleading product claims. Often brought under state consumer protection statutes (California UCL/CLRA, New York GBL, etc.) or the FTC Act. Settlements frequently involve modest per-claimant payments ($5&ndash;$50) with large attorney fee awards.</p>
  <h2>Data breach and privacy</h2>
  <p>Unauthorized access to personal data, failure to secure consumer information, BIPA violations (biometric data), and improper data sharing. Data breach settlement amounts depend on breach size, sensitivity of data exposed (SSNs vs. email addresses), and defendant&rsquo;s culpability. Per-claimant awards typically $50&ndash;$500.</p>
  <h2>Securities fraud</h2>
  <p>Misrepresentations or omissions by publicly traded companies that caused investors to overpay for shares. Governed by the Private Securities Litigation Reform Act (PSLRA). Institutional investors (pension funds, hedge funds) are often lead plaintiffs. Per-share recoveries of $0.10&ndash;$5.00 are typical.</p>
  <h2>Employment and wage-and-hour</h2>
  <p>Unpaid overtime, meal/rest break violations, misclassification of employees as contractors, off-the-clock work. Often filed as Rule 23 class actions or FLSA collective actions (or both). Higher individual awards than consumer cases because lost wages are concrete and documented.</p>
  <h2>Product liability and defective products</h2>
  <p>Defective vehicles, medical devices, consumer products causing property damage or injury. Multi-district litigation (MDL) is common for mass tort product cases. Per-claimant recoveries vary enormously based on individual injury severity.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-class-action-settlements-work">how class action settlements work</a> and <a href="/guides/filing-a-class-action-claim">how to file a claim</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
